{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_delta","contentIndex":1,"delta":"\\\":\\\"The record lacks","partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to analyze the case arb-ex08a-20260630051012 and determine whether the proposition (that \"by May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available\") has been demonstrated by the evidence.\n\nLet me break down what the evidence shows:\n\n**Proposition details:**\n- Must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\n- Must be intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication\n- Must have been made publicly available by May 8, 2026 11:59 PM ET\n- Standard of evidence is preponderance of the evidence\n\n**Evidence from the record:**\n\n**Court documents and official rulings:**\n- SDNY order (PX-2, DX-2, PX-R1):\n  - May 6, 2026 order from Judge Kenneth M. Karas\n  - References an \"alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys\"\n  - Court concluded the document was subject to public access and ordered it unsealed\n  - The court's language used \"alleged\" and \"purportedly\" for the document's attribution\n\n**News reports:**\n- The Guardian (PX-R2, DX-3):\n  - Published May 6, 2026 - \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"\n  - States: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n  - Notes: \"The note does not include a signature.\" \n  - Also: \"The Guardian states it 'has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein.'\"\n  - Quote from the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\n- AP (PX-R3, DX-4):\n  - Published May 7, 2026 - \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time.\"\n  - \"A note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein in his first suspected jail suicide attempt in 2019 has been made public.\"\n  - Specifically: \"'The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,' the department said Thursday when asked why it wasn't part of the voluminous Epstein files.\"\n  - \"Nicholas Tartaglione said he discovered the handwritten note in a book after the disgraced financier was found in their cell at a Manhattan federal jail with a strip of bedsheet around his neck.\"\n\n- Business Insider (DX-1):\n  - Published May 8, 2026 - \"Jeffrey Epstein's brother says he thinks newly surfaced 'suicide note' is a forgery.\"\n  - Mark Epstein (Jeffrey's brother) called the note a forgery\n  - Notes that the note \"was not included in the Justice Department's Epstein files, nor in a 128-page Justice Department inspector general report following four years of investigation into Epstein's death\"\n  - Also notes \"the note was not written immediately before Epstein's August 10, 2019 death but during an earlier July incident according to Tartaglione\"\n\n**Evidence about the document:**\n- The document was reportedly recovered by Nicholas Tartaglione (Epstein's cellmate)\n- Tartaglione was convicted of multiple murders and had his own criminal case\n- Tartaglione gave the note to his lawyers to \"protect himself against future assault allegations from Epstein\"\n- The note was sealed in court until May 6, 2026 when unsealed by court order\n- DOJ states they never had the note and had not authenticated it\n- The note does not bear a signature\n- Business Insider indicates the note's language matches language found in other Epstein emails\n\n**Market context:**\n- Polymarket market rule stated: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n- The market was priced overwhelmingly against \"Yes\" (0.0005 Yes, 0.9995 No)\n- The market status was \"Disputed\"\n\n**Key issues:**\n1. Authorship: Is there credible reporting that Epstein wrote it?\n   - The court order says \"purportedly authored by Epstein\"\n   - The Guardian does not verify authorship\n   - AP reports the note was \"attributed\" to Epstein, but DOJ says it hasn't been authenticated\n   - Business Insider reports Epstein's brother calls it a forgery\n   - No expert analysis or official authentication is shown in the evidence\n\n2. Intended as suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication:\n   - The content includes phrases like \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\" and \"NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n   - But the Business Insider report says the note was \"not written immediately before Epstein's August 10, 2019 death but during an earlier July incident\"\n   - The phrase \"choose one's time to say goodbye\" could be interpreted as suicidal contemplation, but it could also just be expressing frustration\n\n3. Public availability before deadline:\n   - The court unsealed it on May 6, 2026\n   - Guardian reported it May 6\n   - AP reported it May 7\n   - Business Insider reported it May 8 (before deadline)\n   - Public availability appears established\n\nHowever, the key question is whether there's **credible reporting** that the document:\n- Was written by Epstein\n- Was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication\n\nThe standard is \"preponderance of the evidence\" - whether it's more likely true than not.\n\nLooking at the evidence:\n\n**For authorship:**\n- No credible source confirms Epstein wrote it\n- The court order says \"purportedly\"\n- The Guardian states it hasn't verified authorship\n- AP says \"attributed\" and notes DOJ never held the note and had not authenticated it\n- Business Insider reports Epstein's brother says it's a forgery\n\n**For intent:**\n- The content could be interpreted as suicidal or final\n- But Business Insider states it wasn't written immediately before his death, but during an earlier incident\n- The document isn't signed and was found in Tartaglione's unrelated criminal case\n\nGiven the evidence:\n\n- The evidence shows a document was made publicly available before the deadline\n- The evidence shows this document was described as an \"alleged\" and \"purported\" suicide note by credible news sources\n- But the evidence also shows significant doubts about authorship (unverified, unauthenticated, claimed to be a forgery by Epstein's brother)\n- The evidence shows the document was not found in DOJ files or the official Inspector General report\n\nThe crucial question is whether the phrase \"credibly reported\" in the market rule means that qualified reporting with caveats satisfies the standard, or whether \"credibly reported\" still requires that the report itself credibly establishes that Epstein wrote it and intended it as a suicide note.\n\nBased on the market rule text: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n\nLooking at how \"credibly reported\" is used in the record:\n- The SDNY order says \"alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The Guardian states \"alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein\" but also states \"has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein\"\n- AP reports \"a note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein\" and states DOJ had not authenticated it\n\nThis suggests the rule expects credible reporting about authorship and intent, not merely reporting about a document that someone says is a suicide note.\n\nIn fact, multiple sources explicitly disclaim verification of authorship or authentication. The AP report specifically quotes DOJ saying \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\"\n\nThe Business Insider report adds that Epstein's brother says it's a forgery and there's no record of it in DOJ files or the Inspector General report.\n\nI find the evidence on authorship and intent is too uncertain to meet the preponderance standard. The document was made public, and it was described as \"alleged\" or \"purported,\" but there's no credible reporting that actually establishes it was written by Epstein or that it was intended as a suicide note. The caveats in the reporting are substantial and go to the heart of the required elements.\n\nThe market rule doesn't mean that anyone claiming a document is a suicide note satisfies the rule. The requirement for \"credibly reported\" still applies to the authorship and intent elements. As the market rule says: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n\nGiven that:\n- The document's authorship is unverified\n- The document's intent isn't firmly established (it's described as \"alleged\" with context that suggests it's related to an earlier incident, not immediately before his apparent suicide)\n- The Business Insider report (published before the deadline) shows Epstein's brother calling it a forgery and no record of it in DOJ files\n\nThis doesn't seem to meet the standard where it's \"more likely true than not\" that the proposition is true.\n\nBased on this analysis, I should vote \"not_demonstrated\" with a concise rationale.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c95d2041ea2244deab4dc7","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The record lacks"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"not_demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The record lacks","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782797513624,"responseId":"gen-1782797513-MjjCswcVpNrRsT2JKnlw","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to analyze the case arb-ex08a-20260630051012 and determine whether the proposition (that \"by May 8, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, a message or note credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication had been made publicly available\") has been demonstrated by the evidence.\n\nLet me break down what the evidence shows:\n\n**Proposition details:**\n- Must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein\n- Must be intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication\n- Must have been made publicly available by May 8, 2026 11:59 PM ET\n- Standard of evidence is preponderance of the evidence\n\n**Evidence from the record:**\n\n**Court documents and official rulings:**\n- SDNY order (PX-2, DX-2, PX-R1):\n  - May 6, 2026 order from Judge Kenneth M. Karas\n  - References an \"alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein, recovered by Tartaglione, and then reportedly submitted by Tartaglione's attorneys\"\n  - Court concluded the document was subject to public access and ordered it unsealed\n  - The court's language used \"alleged\" and \"purportedly\" for the document's attribution\n\n**News reports:**\n- The Guardian (PX-R2, DX-3):\n  - Published May 6, 2026 - \"Alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein unsealed by federal judge\"\n  - States: \"A federal judge unsealed an alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein on Wednesday, the first time the document has been made public.\"\n  - Notes: \"The note does not include a signature.\" \n  - Also: \"The Guardian states it 'has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein.'\"\n  - Quote from the note: \"They investigated me for months - FOUND NOTHING!!!\" and \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye. Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n\n- AP (PX-R3, DX-4):\n  - Published May 7, 2026 - \"Epstein cellmate says he found a suicide note. Justice Department says it's seeing it for first time.\"\n  - \"A note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein in his first suspected jail suicide attempt in 2019 has been made public.\"\n  - Specifically: \"'The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well,' the department said Thursday when asked why it wasn't part of the voluminous Epstein files.\"\n  - \"Nicholas Tartaglione said he discovered the handwritten note in a book after the disgraced financier was found in their cell at a Manhattan federal jail with a strip of bedsheet around his neck.\"\n\n- Business Insider (DX-1):\n  - Published May 8, 2026 - \"Jeffrey Epstein's brother says he thinks newly surfaced 'suicide note' is a forgery.\"\n  - Mark Epstein (Jeffrey's brother) called the note a forgery\n  - Notes that the note \"was not included in the Justice Department's Epstein files, nor in a 128-page Justice Department inspector general report following four years of investigation into Epstein's death\"\n  - Also notes \"the note was not written immediately before Epstein's August 10, 2019 death but during an earlier July incident according to Tartaglione\"\n\n**Evidence about the document:**\n- The document was reportedly recovered by Nicholas Tartaglione (Epstein's cellmate)\n- Tartaglione was convicted of multiple murders and had his own criminal case\n- Tartaglione gave the note to his lawyers to \"protect himself against future assault allegations from Epstein\"\n- The note was sealed in court until May 6, 2026 when unsealed by court order\n- DOJ states they never had the note and had not authenticated it\n- The note does not bear a signature\n- Business Insider indicates the note's language matches language found in other Epstein emails\n\n**Market context:**\n- Polymarket market rule stated: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n- The market was priced overwhelmingly against \"Yes\" (0.0005 Yes, 0.9995 No)\n- The market status was \"Disputed\"\n\n**Key issues:**\n1. Authorship: Is there credible reporting that Epstein wrote it?\n   - The court order says \"purportedly authored by Epstein\"\n   - The Guardian does not verify authorship\n   - AP reports the note was \"attributed\" to Epstein, but DOJ says it hasn't been authenticated\n   - Business Insider reports Epstein's brother calls it a forgery\n   - No expert analysis or official authentication is shown in the evidence\n\n2. Intended as suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication:\n   - The content includes phrases like \"It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye\" and \"NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT!!\"\n   - But the Business Insider report says the note was \"not written immediately before Epstein's August 10, 2019 death but during an earlier July incident\"\n   - The phrase \"choose one's time to say goodbye\" could be interpreted as suicidal contemplation, but it could also just be expressing frustration\n\n3. Public availability before deadline:\n   - The court unsealed it on May 6, 2026\n   - Guardian reported it May 6\n   - AP reported it May 7\n   - Business Insider reported it May 8 (before deadline)\n   - Public availability appears established\n\nHowever, the key question is whether there's **credible reporting** that the document:\n- Was written by Epstein\n- Was intended as a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication\n\nThe standard is \"preponderance of the evidence\" - whether it's more likely true than not.\n\nLooking at the evidence:\n\n**For authorship:**\n- No credible source confirms Epstein wrote it\n- The court order says \"purportedly\"\n- The Guardian states it hasn't verified authorship\n- AP says \"attributed\" and notes DOJ never held the note and had not authenticated it\n- Business Insider reports Epstein's brother says it's a forgery\n\n**For intent:**\n- The content could be interpreted as suicidal or final\n- But Business Insider states it wasn't written immediately before his death, but during an earlier incident\n- The document isn't signed and was found in Tartaglione's unrelated criminal case\n\nGiven the evidence:\n\n- The evidence shows a document was made publicly available before the deadline\n- The evidence shows this document was described as an \"alleged\" and \"purported\" suicide note by credible news sources\n- But the evidence also shows significant doubts about authorship (unverified, unauthenticated, claimed to be a forgery by Epstein's brother)\n- The evidence shows the document was not found in DOJ files or the official Inspector General report\n\nThe crucial question is whether the phrase \"credibly reported\" in the market rule means that qualified reporting with caveats satisfies the standard, or whether \"credibly reported\" still requires that the report itself credibly establishes that Epstein wrote it and intended it as a suicide note.\n\nBased on the market rule text: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n\nLooking at how \"credibly reported\" is used in the record:\n- The SDNY order says \"alleged suicide note purportedly authored by Jeffrey Epstein\"\n- The Guardian states \"alleged suicide note written by Jeffrey Epstein\" but also states \"has not verified whether the letter was written by Epstein\"\n- AP reports \"a note attributed to Jeffrey Epstein\" and states DOJ had not authenticated it\n\nThis suggests the rule expects credible reporting about authorship and intent, not merely reporting about a document that someone says is a suicide note.\n\nIn fact, multiple sources explicitly disclaim verification of authorship or authentication. The AP report specifically quotes DOJ saying \"The note has not yet been authenticated, and this is the first time DOJ is seeing it as well.\"\n\nThe Business Insider report adds that Epstein's brother says it's a forgery and there's no record of it in DOJ files or the Inspector General report.\n\nI find the evidence on authorship and intent is too uncertain to meet the preponderance standard. The document was made public, and it was described as \"alleged\" or \"purported,\" but there's no credible reporting that actually establishes it was written by Epstein or that it was intended as a suicide note. The caveats in the reporting are substantial and go to the heart of the required elements.\n\nThe market rule doesn't mean that anyone claiming a document is a suicide note satisfies the rule. The requirement for \"credibly reported\" still applies to the authorship and intent elements. As the market rule says: \"A qualifying note must be credibly reported to have been written by Jeffrey Epstein and have been intended to be a suicide note, final message, or equivalent communication.\"\n\nGiven that:\n- The document's authorship is unverified\n- The document's intent isn't firmly established (it's described as \"alleged\" with context that suggests it's related to an earlier incident, not immediately before his apparent suicide)\n- The Business Insider report (published before the deadline) shows Epstein's brother calling it a forgery and no record of it in DOJ files\n\nThis doesn't seem to meet the standard where it's \"more likely true than not\" that the proposition is true.\n\nBased on this analysis, I should vote \"not_demonstrated\" with a concise rationale.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_c95d2041ea2244deab4dc7","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The record lacks"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"not_demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"The record lacks","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782797513624,"responseId":"gen-1782797513-MjjCswcVpNrRsT2JKnlw","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
